'''Apollo 15''' was the ninth manned mission in the [[United States]]' [[Apollo program]], the fourth to [[Moon landing|land]] on the [[Moon]], and the eighth successful manned mission. It was the first of what were termed "[[List of Apollo mission types|J missions]]," long stays on the Moon, with a greater focus on science than had been possible on previous missions. It was also the first mission on which the [[Lunar Roving Vehicle]] was used.

The mission began on July 26, 1971, and ended on August 7. At the time, [[NASA]] called it the most successful manned flight ever achieved.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Audio/Year_in_Review/Events-of-1971/Apollo-14-and-15/12295509436546-9/ |title=1971 Year in Review: Apollo 14 and 15 |work=UPI.com |publisher=[[United Press International]] |year=1971 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref>

Commander [[David Scott]] and Lunar Module Pilot [[James Irwin]] spent three days on the Moon, including 18½ hours outside the [[spacecraft]] on lunar [[extra-vehicular activity]] (EVA). The mission was the first not to land in a [[lunar mare]], instead landing near [[Mons Hadley|Hadley rille]], in an area of the [[Mare Imbrium]] called ''Palus Putredinus'' (Marsh of Decay). The crew explored the area using the first lunar rover, which allowed them to travel much farther from the [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] (LM) lander than had been possible on missions without the rover. They collected {{convert|77|kg}} of lunar surface material. At the same time, Command Module Pilot [[Alfred Worden]] orbited the Moon, using a Scientific Instrument Module (SIM) in the [[Apollo Command/Service Module#Service Module (SM)|Service Module]] (SM) to study the lunar surface and environment in great detail with a panoramic camera, a [[Gamma ray spectrometer|gamma-ray spectrometer]], a mapping camera, a laser [[altimeter]], a [[Mass spectrometry|mass spectrometer]], and a lunar sub-satellite deployed at the end of Apollo 15's stay in [[lunar orbit]] (an Apollo program first).

Although the mission accomplished its objectives, this success was somewhat overshadowed by negative publicity that accompanied public awareness of [[Apollo 15 postage stamp incident|postage stamps]] carried without authorization by the astronauts, who had made plans to sell them upon their return.

